## Sparse Realizations

& [Realization_001_FermatPrimeSeedIdentity] is a dense-node candidate
  + [subject] is 3, 5, 17, 257, 65537
  + [computed_identity] is Fermat-prime identity for F0 through F4
  + [rule_surface] is p = 2^(2^n) + 1 and p - 1 is a pure power of two whose exponent is itself a power of two
  + [computed_orders] is ord_p(2) = 2, 4, 8, 16, 32 for p = 3, 5, 17, 257, 65537
  + [scope] is local identity within the seed focus
  + [boundary] is no claim that these are all Fermat primes in theorem authority or current computational authority

& [Realization_002_Prime641Boundary] is correlated periphery
  + [subject] is 641
  + [computed_relation] is 641 divides F5 because 2^(2^5) is congruent to -1 modulo 641
  + [computed_order] is ord_641(2) = 64
  + [computed_form] is 641 = 5*2^7 + 1
  + [scope] is Fermat-number factor boundary, not Fermat-prime seed identity
  + [meaning] is 641 marks the first visible fracture of the naive Fermat-prime continuation from F0 through F4

& [Realization_003_OverlappingFamilySurfaces] is unresolved periphery
  + [subject] is special-prime family overlap
  + [computed_relation] is the seed Fermat primes are also Proth-form and Pierpont-form primes, while 641 is Proth-form but not Pierpont-form
  + [computed_relation] is 3 is also a Mersenne prime and 5 is both safe and Sophie Germain in the scanned profile
  + [computed_relation] is 641 is also Sophie Germain because 1283 is prime
  + [meaning] is surface resemblance can cross identity boundaries; family overlap is not identity collapse

& [Realization_004_ForgottenSetCandidates] is immediate periphery
  + [candidate] is Mersenne primes
  + [reason] is they are the natural power-of-two mirror family, p = 2^q - 1, and the bounded scan under 2000 found 3, 7, 31, and 127
  + [candidate] is base-2 Wieferich primes
  + [reason] is they are rare Fermat-congruence exceptions, and the bounded scan under 2000 found 1093
  + [candidate] is Proth and Pierpont primes
  + [reason] is they contain or neighbor the Fermat-prime seed surface without sharing the exact Fermat identity
  + [candidate] is irregular primes
  + [reason] is they connect prime oddity to Bernoulli numerators and zeta special values, but they require a separate scan tool before local authority
  + [status] is unresolved_memory_match

& [Realization_005_RHBoundary] is restraint
  + [subject] is RH landscape relevance
  + [meaning] is special prime families can expose local arithmetic constraints in the prime landscape and help train periphery focus
  + [boundary] is RH concerns global zeta-zero structure and prime distribution; finite special-family profiles are not RH evidence by themselves
  + [next_use] is use family profiles to form inspection questions, not theorem claims

